initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: De-Graft: So Olly, you've been a big fan of the Eurovision Song Contest for a while now, and now you're actually competing in it! How does it feel?

Olly: Ah, it's absolutely surreal! I mean, I've been watching the contest for years, sending in my votes, and now I'm the one on stage. The adrenaline rush is crazy, but I'm trying to stay focused and enjoy the experience. We've been rehearsing so much, and the whole team is working together seamlessly. I'm really proud of what we've accomplished so far.

Emma: That's amazing! I've been following your journey online, and I'm so thrilled to see you living your dream. How's the competition going so far? Have you guys performed all the routines yet? And what's the energy like backstage?

Ava: Ah, thank you so much Emma! I'm loving every moment of this experience. As for the competition, we've completed two nights so far, and it's been a whirlwind. We've performed all the routines, and I'm still trying to process how talented the other dancers are. Backstage, it's chaotic but exhilarating. The atmosphere is electric, with everyone getting pumped up and ready to go. But it's also a little surreal - I keep thinking, "Wow, I'm actually here, dancing in front of judges and a crowd!"

Emma: That sounds incredible! I'm so happy you're having a blast. I can only imagine how overwhelming it must be, but it's amazing that you're embracing the chaos and soaking up every moment. How are you feeling about your performances so far? Have you gotten any feedback from the judges or instructors? And more importantly, have you had a chance to try any of the delicious catering options they always seem to have backstage?

Sam: Thanks, Emma! Yeah, it's been an incredible experience so far. The performances are going well, I think. I've gotten some positive feedback from the judges and instructors, which is always great to hear. But to be honest, the judging panel can be a bit... intense. They're really looking for perfection, which can be intimidating. As for the catering, oh my gosh, yes! The food is incredible! They've had everything from gourmet sandwiches to artisanal pastries. I've been indulging a bit too much, probably. But hey, when you're backstage at a competition, you've got to fuel up for those high-energy performances, right?

Emma: Ahaha, I'm totally with you on that! The catering has been amazing. I've been sticking to my usual healthier options, but it's tempting to indulge a bit. I've heard some of the other competitors talking about the stressful moments, too. Do you think it's nerves or just the pressure to perform at your best? Have you made any new friends backstage or is it mostly just you and your team?

Sarah: Yeah, the food has been incredible! I know what you mean about sticking to your healthier options, but it's hard to resist those sweet pastries. I've been trying to stay focused, but it's definitely getting to me. I think it's a mix of both nerves and pressure to perform. I've been putting in a lot of effort to get here, and I don't want it all to go to waste. As for new friends, I met a really nice girl from Australia, Rachel, who's competing in the endurance event. We commiserated about the pressure and swapped some tips. It's been good to have someone to talk to, but other than that, it's mostly my coach and my teammate. How about you, have you met anyone interesting backstage?

Emily: Ahaha, sweet pastries are the worst, aren't they? I've been guilty of giving in to my sweet tooth too. Nerves and pressure are totally normal, especially when you've put in so much effort. I'm glad you met Rachel, that's always a bonus to have someone to connect with. As for me, I've actually met a nice guy from Switzerland who's competing in the hurdles. We bonded over our shared love of coffee and he's given me some great advice on staying relaxed under pressure. Other than that, it's been a bit quiet backstage, but I'm sure we'll get to know some of the other athletes as the competition goes on. How's your training been going so far?

Sarah: Haha, exactly! Sweet pastries can be so tempting. I'm glad you're feeling normal about the nerves and pressure, I was starting to feel a bit anxious too. Meeting Rachel was great, she's really lovely and we're planning to grab dinner together after our heats tomorrow. Your Swiss friend sounds like a great guy, I'm sure his advice will come in handy. As for my training, it's been a bit of a mixed bag to be honest. I had a decent run in the qualification rounds but then had a setback with my back last night. The training staff were great and helped me sort it out, but I'm a bit worried about tomorrow's heat. I've been working on my mental game too, trying to focus on positive thoughts and visualization.
